  <entry>
    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w35042</id>
    <title>Building Opportunity: The Intergenerational Effects of Chilean School Construction</title>
    <updated>2026-05-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Adrienne Lucas &amp; Patrick McEwan</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;In 1965–1966, Chile built and staffed thousands of new primary classrooms in supply-constrained communities. Using a quasi-experimental design and large census samples, we show that childhood exposure to school construction substantially improved the schooling and labor market outcomes of adults and closed a persistent female disadvantage in school attainment. Women’s exposure to the policy had large intergenerational spillovers on their children’s on-time grade progression and completed schooling. The marginal value of public funds is 13, including direct effects on adults and intergenerational spillovers.</content>
